title: pop_art
body: Pop art is an art movement that emerged in the [[United Kingdom]] and the United States during the mid- to late-1950s.The movement presented a challenge to traditions of fine art by including imagery from popular and mass culture, such as advertising, comic books and mundane mass-produced objects. One of its aims is to use images of popular culture in art, emphasizing the banal or kitschy elements of any culture, most often through the use of irony. It is also associated with the artists' use of mechanical means of reproduction or rendering techniques. In pop art, material is sometimes visually removed from its known context, isolated, or combined with unrelated material.

title: andy_warhol
body: Andy Warhol (August 6, 1928 – February 22, 1987) was an American visual artist, film director, producer, and leading figure in the [[pop art]] movement. His works explore the relationship between artistic expression, advertising, and celebrity culture that flourished by the 1960s, and span a variety of media, including painting, silkscreening, [[photography]], film, and [[sculpture]].

title: james_hunt
body:
[b]James Simon Wallis Hunt[/b] (29 August 1947 – 15 June 1993)was a British racing driver who won the Formula One World Championship in 1976. After retiring from racing in 1979, Hunt became a media commentator and businessman.

Beginning his racing career in touring car racing, Hunt progressed into Formula Three, where he attracted the attention of the Hesketh Racing team and soon came under their wing. Hunt's often reckless and action-packed exploits on track earned him the nickname "Hunt the Shunt" (shunt, as a British motor-racing term, means "crash"). Hunt entered Formula One in 1973, driving a March 731 entered by the Hesketh Racing team. He went on to win for Hesketh, driving their own Hesketh 308 car, in both World Championship and non-championship races, before joining the McLaren team at the end of 1975. In his first year with McLaren, Hunt won the 1976 World Drivers' Championship, and he remained with the team for a further two years, although with less success, before moving to the Wolf team in early 1979. Following a string of races in which he failed to finish, Hunt retired from driving halfway through the 1979 season.

After retiring from motor racing, he became a motor racing commentator for the BBC. He died from a heart attack when he was 45

The 1976 F1 battle between Niki Lauda and James Hunt was dramatised in the 2013 film Rush

title: oberth_class_space_destroyer
body:
A fictional [[military]] [[spacecraft]] from the [[MACROSS]] [[science fiction]] series. It first appeared in the [[Choujikuu Yousai Macross]] TV series from 1982.

The [b]Oberth Class Space Destroyer[/b] (オーベルト級 [i]Ōberuto-kyū[/i]) is a human built warship designed as the primary combat starship of the new [[u.n._spacy|United Nations Spacy]] fleet. 

Built with OverTechnology and armed with [[nuclear_weapon|reaction weaponry]], the Oberth compensated for lightweight armor (the only weakness) with a simple, easy-to-build structure, high maneuverability and excellent firepower. A direct hit from one of the Oberth reaction missiles could incapacitate a [[Zentradi]] Standard Battleship of the [[Thurvel-Salan]] Class.

title: ewac_jegan
body:
[b]RGM-89DEW EWAC Jegan[/b]

The RGM-89DEW EWAC Jegan is a reconnaissance version of the RGM-89D [[Jegan D Type]]. It has enhanced sensing capabilities thanks to a large sensor unit attached to the head, a second sensor unit on its left forearm, and a large camera unit on its right forearm. The sensor unit on the left forearm has a laser communication device, allowing it to relay gathered information back to the mothership. Since it was never intended to engage in direct combat, the suit's weaponry is kept to a minimum and consisted of a beam saber, a beam rifle and three hand grenades. Its heat emission is extremely low, making it difficult to detect via thermal detection.

title: fez_hat
body:
A short, cylindrical, peakless hat with a tassel on top, commonly found in red. Otherwise known as a tarboosh/tarboush.

Existing in some shape or form around the Mediterranean for centuries, it was popularized by the Ottoman Empire in the early 19th century, with the intent of replacing the turban and act as a unifying piece of clothes (though ultimately gaining various distinct interpretations). Would ultimately be banned in Turkey in 1925 along with the turban under Atatürk to ensure adoption of Western hats, with it only being lifted in 2014. It is worn by various Muslim communities internationally today, as well as Masonic groups.

title: h&k_g36
body:
The [b]G36[/b] is a 5.56×45mm NATO [[assault rifle]], designed in early 1990s and manufactured by [[Heckler & Koch]] in Germany. It was intended to supplant the failed [[H&K G11|G11]] project and the [[H&K G41|G41]] which was too heavy, the G36 features a conventional configuration with short-stroke piston operation. Notable variants include the shorter [[H&K G36K|G36K]], the shortest [[H&K G36C|G36C]], and the [[h&k mg36|MG36]] [[light machine gun]].

The [[weapon]] is characterized by a large carrying handle with an integrated [[optical sight]] and skeletonized [[folding stock]]. It lacks a front sight post as well. The G36 can be fitted with a [[bipod]] or an [[underbarrel grenade launcher]].

title: zastava_m56
body:
The [b]Zastava M56[/b] is a blowback [[submachine gun]] of [[yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] origin, chambered in 7.62×25mm Tokarev [[ammunition|round]], designed for use with the Yugoslav People's Army. Initially a state-funded product, it was later produced by Zastava Arms and introduced in 1961. It saw use in a number of conflicts following the breakup of former Yugoslavia. The M56's external design is based on the captured [[MP40]], both [[weapon]]s featuring an [[folding stock|underfolding stock]], but easily distinguished from the MP40 by its increased length, charging handle on the right side, curved [[magazine (weapon)|magazine]] (32-round is its standard capacity), and [[bayonet]] attachment support. It has similarities with the [[PPS submachine gun]].

Inexpensive and simple to produce and maintain, the M56 also proved to be quite effective at range over its German counterpart due to its 7.62×25mm cartridge having significantly higher velocity than the 9×19mm.

h1. See also

title: battle_of_sicily

title: airpot
body:
A portable vacuum insulated hot beverage dispenser with a glass or stainless steel liner inside. Airpots can be filled with hot beverages such as [[tea]] and [[coffee]] and are used to keep beverages warm for several hours. Since airpots do not require electricity, they are easy to use outdoors or in temporary locations such as conference rooms and formal receptions.

It resembles a portable version of a [[water boiler]], though it doesn't have the heating function it does.

title: vigneron_submachine_gun
body:
The [b]Vigneron[/b] is a 9mm Parabellum [[submachine gun]] manufactured in Belgium during the 1950s, designed by a retired Belgian army Colonel, Georges Vigneron. It was intended to replace the [[Sten gun|Sten]]. It features few elements from previous SMG designs, such as tubular upper receiver and sliding wire buttstock that resembles [[m3 submachine gun|M3 Grease Gun]] one. The [[gun]] is relatively accurate on semi-auto mode due to its barrel length.

This tag applies to all variants, the original Vigneron M1 and the improved M2.

title: escape_ad
body:

Notably, the actual gameplay is nothing like the advertised gameplay.

Has become a [[meme]] due to how pervasive they are, due to their use by games such as [[Hero Wars]], [[Hero Rescue]] (even if reflective of actual gameplay), and most famously, the "-scapes" series of games by [[Playrix]].

title: arisaka
body:
The [b]Arisaka[/b] family of [[bolt action]] rifles were a series of Japanese weapons designed by Colonel Nariakira Arisaka. They were the standard weapons of the Japanese Empire from 1898 to 1945 and were used in [[World War I]] and [[World War II]]. 

The Arisaka rifles were derived in part from the German Mauser, especially the 5-round internal magazine fed by a stripper clip. The most common versions were the 6.5x50mm Type 38 long rifle and 7.7x58mm Type 99 short rifle. Less common but notable variants are the folding-bayonet Type 44 carbine and Type 97 sniper rifle (both derived from the Type 38), and the Type 2 paratrooper rifle (based on the Type 99). 

Arisaka rifles were marked with [[kikumon|the Imperial Seal of Japan]] (a Chrysanthemum), designating them as the property of the Emperor.

body:
An object from [[Berserk]]. A stone with the shape and size of an egg, with facial features that can:

* Be randomly arranged, as in post #348718.
* Form a grotesque blood-crying face, as in post #455148.

[spoiler]The Behelit acts as a key to the realm of the God Hand. Through the working of Causality, it finds its way to the hand of a person who eventually reaches his or her lowest point of despair, upon which the Behelit activates by forming the grotesque blood-crying face above and screaming. This summons the God Hand for a special ceremony that usually ends with the bearer sacrificing someone dear to them in order to become an Apostle.

Most Behelits are blue, green or yellow. But once every 216 years, a special crimson Behelit makes its way to a chosen bearer, a charismatic figure and a leader of men who is destined to become the next member of the God Hand during the Eclipse.[/spoiler]

body:
[b]Private First Class Robert "Lucky Peaches" Hugh Leckie[/b] (December 18, 1920 – December 24, 2001) was a [[united_states_marine_corps|United States Marine]] and an author of books about the [[military]] history of the [[United States]], Catholic history and culture, sports books, fiction books, autobiographies, and children's books. As a young man, he served with the 1st Marine Division during [[World War II]]; his service as a machine gunner and a scout during the war greatly influenced his work.

Leckie's war memoir, [i]Helmet for My Pillow[/i], along with [[eugene_bondurant_sledge|Eugene B. Sledge]]'s book [i]With the Old Breed[/i], formed the basis for the HBO series [[The Pacific]] (2010), the follow-up series to [[Band of Brothers]] (2001). [b]The Guadalcanal Campaign[/b], also known as [b]The Battle of Guadalcanal[/b] and codenamed [b]Operation Watchtower[/b] by [[united_states|American]] forces, was a [[military]] campaign fought between 7 August 1942 and 9 February 1943 on and around the island of [[guadalcanal_(island)|Guadalcanal]] in the Pacific theater of [[World War II]]. 

It was the first major land offensive by Allied forces against the Empire of [[Japan]]. It ended in a major Allied [[victory]] that caused the complete Japanese withdrawal from the island and the beginning of Allied offensive operations in the Pacific Ocean.

title: battle_of_peleliu
body:
[b]The Battle of Peleliu[/b], codenamed [b]Operation Stalemate II[/b] by the US [[military]], was fought between the [[United States]] and [[Japan]] during the Mariana and Palau Islands campaign of [[World War II]], from 15 September to 27 November 1944, on the [[island]] of Peleliu.

US Marines of the 1st Marine Division and then soldiers of the US Army's 81st Infantry Division fought to capture an airfield on the small coral island of Peleliu. The battle was part of a larger offensive campaign known as [b]Operation Forager[/b], which ran from June to November 1944 in the Pacific Theater.

It ended in a very costly American [[victory]].

The battle is extensively featured in the American historical [[war]] drama series, [[The Pacific]].

This gesture, typically seen in fiction such as anime, manga, rather old films or dramas, and typically done by young boys, indicates one's pride, confidence, and/or [[shy]]ness.

title: 1980_iranian_embassy_siege
body:
A [b][[historical event]][/b] that took place from 30 April to 5 May [[1980]], after a group of six [[gun|armed]] men stormed the [[Iran]]ian embassy on Prince's Gate in South Kensington, [[London]]. The [[terrorist|gunmen]] were [[Iran]]ian Arab [[terrorist]]s campaigning for sovereignty of Khuzestan Province. They took 26 [[hostage]]s, including embassy staff, several visitors, and a [[police]] officer. 

By the sixth day, the gunmen proceed to [[murder|kill]] a hostage and [[throwing|threw]] his [[corpse|body]] out of the embassy on the evening. The [[Special Air Service]] (SAS) initiated "Operation Nimrod" to rescue the hostages, abseiling from the roof and forcing entry through the [[window]]s. During the 17-minute raid they rescued all but one of the remaining hostages and killed five of the six hostage-takers. The sole remaining gunman served 27 years in [[prison]].

The SAS raid became the subject of multiple documentaries and works of fiction, including several films and TV series.

Following the end of World War 2, he would remain imprisoned until 1959, when he had been released after "successful reeducation" and "Communist remodeling", with endorsement from the [[china|CCP]]. With the help of the information about nasods and broken nasod parts inside the library, Add creates the nasod Dynamo and manages to get out. Due to time flowing different inside the library, Add ends up in the future where Elsword's story takes place. He has an obsession with rare nasod codes that will allow him to return to the past. title: croupier
body:
A croupier or dealer is someone appointed at a gambling table to assist in the conduct of the game, especially in the distribution of bets and payouts. Croupiers are typically employed by casinos.

Originally a 'croupier' meant one who stood behind a gambler, with extra reserves of cash to back him up during a gambling session. The word derived from 'croup' (the rump of a horse) and was by way of analogy to one who rode behind on horseback. It later came to refer to one who was employed to collect the money from a gaming-table.

A female croupier's uniform usually consists of a shirt and tie with a [[vest]], and a [[miniskirt]] or slacks.
